Lille mr. Richard Southell
I have not answered yo of 5th curtt because sence I have been almost in the other worl
been gereft through the cy of an medle as the common provers is, I have been a bleading
out of my nose well 3 dayes which if had not been timely stopped, had carried mee away
though God be chancked I begn to amend, letters were, al most ready to desire y atitance
Intrim send here a bill for ƒ300- on Pierre Janstens for which where due pray pocure
the need full, & in case itt bee nott duely accepted & payd, deliver itt to m. Jande Walle
with itt protest, accord. to thes anneped note, which will pay itt: my indisposition keeps
mee from all affaires, so that I want mnel monny, could you spare a £100- where this shall
be receaved, yon shall oblige mee. I have the menaging of all concernis with you to yd
self, & hope att the latter end of they eare to finde an acctt. to content, inclosed patt. of my
fabrique, by which you may ourly see the spinning, for they are not prest, I make all
cullours I will & I can selly att ƒ4:10, aw ell here, hetherto have sold all as so one
as come In the ware house, which keeps back all sonts of english cloathes from 8 to 20 a 11 ƒ
ayd, in case you finde them well I could send ferw for abryall, Inclosed a letter which
is brought mee, with a little pacquett, butt I did not send that, as beeng some what
to big to 90 with the post witheont yo order I rest

London Henry Colliys
Sr. In answer to yd of 30: past returne you thanckes, for what you didfor
mee in selling my cloth which is noted accordingly as for TH. I have consides
yd charity to be leave him as acristian & not as a papist, I assure you up on
my salvation that no papist in the worltd can or may serare falsly
without preiudice tohis soule, itt beeng contrary not onely to the commans
of god, butt against nature I have not yett sponen with herreynes butt have
sent for him & shall do according to yd order for I should be glad to do m. Hartopp
any service & kininess I have sence f seen much indisposed of blaeding
out of my nose, which hadd almost earried mee away, had not been preen
preveated bj providence that hath brought mee so lose inforce, & weach
of boddy, that I must sett all affaires aside for some monthes, & live
some where in the countrey o that I supose to be all & Ianu nent
a broad god willing therefore desire you not to draw on mee, for mind
absence there shall be little or nothing to do, & will not leave my peoghe
straightned att home for mony for please to do mee that hindress te
spare mee till my returne intrim my book keeper hath al most fiuwished
all acctts & you shall have yd botimes & so remaine
a 22 ditto

London Henry Maynard
S. my last to you was on the 18: curitt to which referre you because sence non
from you so have onely to desire you to send mee pr. vere first 8 or 10
worster frises all drap cullours made up as the last as also in prijses not
exceeding 4 N.6 a yd butt rather under that price take not ce that they
be of a lovely drap cullour, & if you meet them to content buy½ to
bemade 6 duble, adto the same pack 4 white devous hire bayes redlists
of about 26: pence ayd butt they must be of the right sort of a good
woll, curious white & a lovely broad redlist a gouverno, send also 4 swans
kins white bayes blew usts of the green streephens, & lett that pack be
wrapped with 4 or 5 white kersies a 22 yd provided you can have them att
30 a 31m at furthest & good accordingly n this please to be as expedient
as possible, because all my fises are gon i& they sell onely this & the
next month -if you could meet with 20 or 25 white kersies 22 yd
long & att llast agard & 3 enches broad, good woll & white ware under
30 a peece you might buy & send them from london because
the time should be past to have any from the north there fore onele
you or could meet them with all the mentioned qualities I should
rather have non a governo: my disposition beginces to amend (god be
thancked, & hope to be att brussels in few dayes to reinforce the
casl to make you the neceassary remises which is the needfull aft
